Ah, good to see you fellow soldiers! It would appear we have less than 100 hours left until the end of November, quite the milestone really! I have an interesting discussion topic, just for the few of you that remain.

- The best way to beat NNN is to overload your schedule with things to do. Since I don't have much of a life outside of media, I bought myself a couple of games to keep myself busy. Sonic Frontiers, Sonic Adventure 2 and just today, Sonic Mania. With there being so much to do, I won't have any free time, nor any free thoughts on failing the challenge.

But enough about me, what about you? I'd be interested in hearing what games you soldiers have been playing to keep yourself busy. Today was a bit easier for me, but yesterday was still the hardest. My problem comes in at the morning when I'm just waking up or trying to fall asleep so if any of you soldiers have any suggestions on how to make that whole hassle easier I'd love to hear it.

Figured that the best way to keep people busy / motivated was to create some topics to discuss with each other, we're all in this after all! It's 4 days soldiers, you can keep counting with a singular hand, just don't use said-hand to fail the challenge. Keep it up soldiers, we're almost there! o7

"Now, wait a minute Peter. We uh, we need to talk."

"Oh, we can talk later."

"Well, we can talk now. If you'd let me."

"What do we have to talk about, why now?" 

"Because we haven't talked at all for so long, your Aunt May and I don't even know who you are anymore. You, shirked your chores. You–you have all those weird experiments in–in your room. You–you start fights at school. I don't-"

"I didn't start that fight, I told you that."

"What was I supposed to do, run away?"

"No, no, you're not supposed to run away, but. Pete, look. You're changing, I know, I went through exactly the same thing at your age."

"No, not exactly."

"Peter, these are the years when a man changes into the man he's going to become the rest of his life. Just be careful who you change into. This guy, Flash Thompson. He probably deserved what happened. But just because you can beat him up, doesn't give you the right to. Remember. With great power, comes great responsibility." 

"Are you afraid that I'm going to turn into some kind of criminal? Quit worrying about me, okay? Something's different, I'll figure it out. Stop lecturing me, please." 

"I don't mean to lecture, and I don't to preach. And I know I'm not your father."

"Then stop pretending to be!" 

"... Right. I'll pick you up here at 10."

Capt. Hector's Log book. November 27th, 1887:

The light here is very different. The ice-crystal walls are invisible behind a soft and luminous fog. Even the air is warmer. My shadow paces me, stalking the boundaries of the fog. KNOW YOURSELF, a voice intones.

"This," the Mechanic says, very quietly, "is as far as we go. Let's get what we came for, and get out. I don't want to see what's in the fog - not again." Has he been here all along? I supposed nothing is certain in Frostfound. 

The Mechanic fumbles in the drifting mist on the floor. (His shadow does the same. From within the fog, as it scrapes away in imitation, there is a dull grating noise, as of claws on rock.) He comes up with a stone piglet, small enough to lie comfortably on the palm of his hand. Its eyes are bright pearls.

"I'm sorry," the Mechanic confesses. "My imagination is rather literal." He stows the pig away out of sight. "Now please can we go? I can feel my teeth chattering, out there." He walks out without waiting for me. Should I continue into Frostfound? I am so close to the heart of it, perhaps if I stay a little longer...

No.

I walk away from the heart of Frostfound. Perhaps something are never meant to be learned.

I prayed to Salt, Storm, and Stone that I will survive this voyage, for the deep dark zee is unforgiving.

And if you don’t count sleep, 8 hours of sleep times 4 days is 32 hours of sleep across the 4 days, subtract that from 24 hours in a day times 4 days ((24x4)-(8x4)) = 64 hours left, or 2 days and 16 hours. And on days 28-30 I have classes at college, which amounts to 435 minutes or 7.25 hours, 64-7.25 = 56.75 hours. Then when you consider 30 minutes to get ready for, walk to, and then return to dorm from each class, that’s another 2.5 hours, down to 55.25. Then if I spend an hour and a half each day eating meals, that’s 6 hours, down to 49.25. This applies to me personally, not sure about you folks out there, but my college is an 8 hour drive from my house, and that means for me there’s actually 41.25 eligible hours left, so less than two days.
